most appropriate initial investigation for delayed puberty?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone age X-ray","Chromosomal analysis","Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain","Bone mineral density scan","Testicular ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone age X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E of the left wrist and hand is the most appropriate initial investigation for delayed puberty. It helps assess skeletal maturation and predict growth potential. A delayed bone age is typically seen in constitutional delay of growth and puberty, while normal bone age may suggest other pathologies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other investigations may be appropriate in specific circumstances but are not first-line:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChromosomal analysis\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated if a genetic disorder such as Klinefelter syndrome is suspected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging of the brain\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated if central causes of hypogonadism are suspected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone mineral density scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely performed in the initial workup of delayed puberty\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if testicular pathology is suspected but is not a first-line investigation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter bone age assessment, further investigations are guided by clinical findings and may include hormonal studies, particularly follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinising hormone, and testosterone or oestradiol levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bone age assessment using wrist X-ray is a key investigation in delayed puberty to determine skeletal maturation.","Delayed puberty is defined as no breast development by age 13 in girls or no testicular enlargement by age 14 in boys.","Bone age is typically delayed in constitutional delay of growth and puberty but may be normal in hypogonadism."],"references":["Elhakeem A, Frysz M, Tilling K, Tobias JH, Lawlor DA. Association Between Age at Puberty and Bone Accrual From 10 to 25 Years of Age. JAMA Netw Open. 2019 Aug 2;2(8):e198918. doi: 10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2019.8918. PMID: 31397863; PMCID: PMC6692837.","Gilsanz V, Chalfant J, Kalkwarf H, Zemel B, Lappe J, Oberfield S, Shepherd J, Wren T, Winer K. Age at onset of puberty predicts bone mass in young adulthood. J Pediatr. 2011 Jan;158(1):100-5, 105.e1-2. doi: 10.1016/j.jpeds.2010.06.054. Epub 2010 Aug 24. PMID: 20797727; PMCID: PMC4767165.","Cousminer DL, Mitchell JA, Chesi A, Roy SM, Kalkwarf HJ, Lappe JM, Gilsanz V, Oberfield SE, Shepherd JA, Kelly A, McCormack SE, Voight BF, Zemel BS, Grant SF. Genetically Determined Later Puberty Impacts Lowered Bone Mineral Density in Childhood and Adulthood. J Bone Miner Res. 2018 Mar;33(3):430-436. doi: 10.1002/jbmr.3320. Epub 2017 Nov 17. PMID: 29068475; PMCID: PMC5839967.","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60108"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16277"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60108"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T22:10:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T22:58:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8968"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74614"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c"